3. Pluralistic Prosperity: The acknowledgment that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built at the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best suit their needs.
The United States, Europe, and Japan have generated comparable levels of prosperity in the long term.
Yet their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social security systems, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models" – a different one every decade – is then presented as a great success, which one should emulate.
The most successful societies of the future will allow room for experiments and permit further evolution of their institutions.
A world economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will tend to foster rather than suppress such experimental openness and evolutionary development.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may seem harmless.
But they carry powerful implications that collide with the prevailing views of globalization supporters.
Such an implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the tools to shape and preserve their own institutions—in other words, to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries may retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules protecting consumer health and safety – and that they should be allowed to do so by possibly erecting barriers at their borders when trade is demonstrably threatening domestic practices that enjoy broad public support.
If the advocates of globalization are correct, the call for such protective measures will fail due to lack of evidence or support.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve to ensure that opposing values— the advantages of open economies and the advantages of maintaining national regulations—both receive appropriate attention in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in the financial sector to maintain values and rules within one's own country should not be confused with the use of such restrictions to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries would find unacceptable.
They should equally not allow the USA or the EU to use trade sanctions or other pressure tools to change labor market rules, environmental policies, or financial regulations in other countries.
Countries have a right to diversity, not to forced convergence.
