6. International Economic Agreements on the Regulation of Interaction Between National Institutions: Relying on the fact that national states provide the basic regulatory functions of the world economy does not mean that we should do without international rules.
The Bretton Woods system ultimately also had clear rules, even though these were limited in scope and depth.
A complete catch-as-catch-can would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the global economy that help vehicles of different sizes, shapes, and speeds to navigate around each other, rather than prescribing an identical car or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive to achieve a maximum level of globalization that is in harmony with the preservation of space for diversity within national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot enjoy the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where this actually takes place, within the national states.
When states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
Therefore, other, less liberal rules must apply to undemocratic states.
These are the principles that the architects of the next world economic order must accept.
The most important thing is that they must accept the ultimate paradox that illustrates each of these principles: globalization works best when it is not taken too far.
